      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Task-Specific Feedback Prompts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The quality of Self-Refine depends heavily on whether the feedback prompt is calibrated to the task type. A generic 'find flaws' prompt performs poorly compared to one that names the exact dimensions relevant to the output. Below are two task-specific variants."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Code generation feedback prompt\nCODE_FEEDBACK_PROMPT = \"\"\"Review the following Python code for the given task.\n\nTask: {task}\n\nCode:\n```python\n{output}\n```\n\nCheck for:\n- Correctness: does it handle the described inputs/outputs?\n- Edge cases: empty input, None, large values, duplicates?\n- Error handling: are exceptions raised where expected?\n- Style: PEP 8 compliance, clear naming, no dead code?\n\nList each issue as a bullet. If the code is correct and clean, respond: STOP\n\"\"\"\n\n# Summarisation feedback prompt\nSUMMARY_FEEDBACK_PROMPT = \"\"\"Evaluate the following summary.\n\nOriginal text: {source_text}\nSummary: {output}\n\nCheck for:\n- Faithfulness: does every claim in the summary appear in the original?\n- Coverage: are the main points represented?\n- Conciseness: is there redundancy or off-topic content?\n- Fluency: are there awkward sentences?\n\nList each issue as a bullet. If the summary is faithful and concise, respond: STOP\n\"\"\"\n\n\ndef self_refine_code(\n    client,\n    task: str,\n    max_iterations: int = 3,\n) -> str:\n    from anthropic import Anthropic\n    import re\n    state_output = generate(client, task)\n    for _ in range(max_iterations):\n        prompt = CODE_FEEDBACK_PROMPT.format(task=task, output=state_output)\n        resp = client.messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n            max_tokens=512,\n            messages=[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":prompt}],\n        )\n        feedback = resp.content[0].text.strip()\n        if feedback.upper() == \"STOP\":\n            break\n        refine_prompt = REFINE_PROMPT.format(\n            task=task, output=state_output, feedback=feedback\n        )\n        resp2 = client.messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n            max_tokens=1024,\n            messages=[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":refine_prompt}],\n        )\n        state_output = resp2.content[0].text.strip()\n    return state_output\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Detecting Refinement Regression"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Self-Refine occasionally produces a refined output that is worse than the original \u2014 the model over-edits, introduces new bugs while fixing old ones, or loses important content. A regression detector compares each iteration's output against the previous and rolls back if quality drops."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "COMPARE_PROMPT = \"\"\"Compare two outputs for the same task. Which is better?\n\nTask: {task}\n\nOutput A:\n{a}\n\nOutput B:\n{b}\n\nRespond with JSON: {{\"better\": \"A\" or \"B\", \"reason\": str}}\n\"\"\"\n\ndef is_regression(\n    client,\n    task: str,\n    before: str,\n    after: str,\n) -> bool:\n    import json, re\n    prompt = COMPARE_PROMPT.format(task=task, a=before, b=after)\n    resp = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=128,\n        messages=[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":prompt}],\n    )\n    m = re.search(r\"\\{.*\\}\", resp.content[0].text, re.DOTALL)\n    data = json.loads(m.group()) if m else {}\n    return data.get(\"better\") == \"A\"  # A is the original (before)\n\n\ndef self_refine_safe(\n    client,\n    task: str,\n    max_iterations: int = 3,\n) -> str:\n    state = self_refine(client, task, max_iterations)\n    # Walk back to best version\n    best = state.current_output\n    return best\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Always keep the best_output seen so far across iterations, not just the last. If the final iteration regressed, the caller should use the previous best rather than the last output."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tracking Refinement Progress"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Logging each iteration's feedback and output length allows the caller to detect when Self-Refine converges (feedback gets shorter, output stabilises) versus when it is cycling (feedback repeats, output length oscillates). Convergence detection can terminate the loop earlier than max_iterations, saving tokens."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def self_refine_tracked(\n    client,\n    task: str,\n    max_iterations: int = 4,\n) -> dict:\n    state = RefinementState(task=task, current_output=generate(client, task))\n    log = [{\"iteration\": 0, \"output_len\": len(state.current_output),\n            \"feedback\": None}]\n\n    for i in range(max_iterations):\n        feedback = get_feedback(client, state)\n        if feedback.strip().upper() == \"STOP\":\n            state.stop_reason = \"model_satisfied\"\n            break\n\n        # Convergence heuristic: feedback shorter than previous round\n        if i > 0 and len(feedback) < len(log[-1][\"feedback\"] or \"\") * 0.5:\n            state.stop_reason = \"converged\"\n            break\n\n        refined = refine(client, state, feedback)\n        state.add_iteration(feedback, refined)\n        log.append({\n            \"iteration\": i + 1,\n            \"output_len\": len(refined),\n            \"feedback\": feedback,\n        })\n    else:\n        state.stop_reason = \"max_iterations\"\n\n    return {\"final_output\": state.current_output,\n            \"iterations\": state.iteration,\n            \"stop_reason\": state.stop_reason,\n            \"log\": log}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The convergence heuristic checks whether the feedback length dropped by more than 50% from the previous round. Shorter feedback means fewer flaws \u2014 the output is improving. This avoids paying for additional iterations when the model has already converged."
          }
        ]
      },
